# OREKA

*Echoes of the Elemental Dawn*

## THE CANON BIBLE

Definitive Campaign Setting Reference — Version 2.6

*Merged from Worldbuilding Guide, Canon Audit, Update Tracker v3.1, and** **Author Rulings*

Compatible with D&D 3.5e Open Game License

March 2026

## 1. THE WORLD OF OREKA — COSMOLOGICAL FOUNDATIONS

Oreka is a land-dominant spherical world with no oceans and no traditional continents. It has two moons. It was forged from the Primordial Chaos by the four Elemental Lords: the Lord of Stone, the Lady of Fire, the Lady of the Sea (Lady Tempest), and the Youngest Brother (the Wind Lord / Trickster). The world’s only major bodies of water are two colossal inland freshwater seas—the Kailian Sea in the north and the Apelian Sea in the south—connected by the Sea Falls.

The Kailian Sea is cold and storm-wracked with stony cliffs, while the Apelian Sea is warm and sediment-rich.

The world was shaped through divine collaboration: the Lady of Fire ignited light, the Sea quenched fury with cooling waters, the Wind breathed life into the world’s rotation, and the Lord of Stone laid down the earth’s bones. From their cooperation, Oreka was born—radiant, fertile, and alive with elemental potential. This collaborative origin means that every biome, landform, and creature in Oreka carries the fingerprints of multiple elements, never just one.

### The Elemental Lords

| **Lord** | **Element** | **Domain** | **Role in**** ****Creation** | **Current**** ****Status** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Lord of Stone | Earth | Mountains, deep earth, stability | Laid the world’s foundations | COMATOSE — side effect of the second assault gate (even the Dómnathar do not know this is happening) |
| Lady of Fire | Fire | Volcanoes, forges, passion | Ignited light and warmth; created Dwarves | ACTIVE — holding back the Abyss Circle and working to destroy the first gate |
| Lady of the Sea / Lady Tempest | Water | Rivers, seas, tides, change | Shaped waterways; created Halflings | ACTIVE — holding back the Abyss Circle alongside the Lady of Fire |
| Youngest Brother / Wind Lord / Trickster | Air/Wind | Sky, storms, art, freedom | Breathed life; created Elves; blessed the creation of Humans | EXILED — kicked out of Oreka in the past; currently trying to find a way back |

**DM NOTE:** *The Elemental Lords’ current status is DM-facing** **information. Most Kin do not know what happened to their creators. The** **Lord of Stone’s coma is caused by a second assault gate—a separate** **gate from the Silence Breach—and even the Dómnathar are unaware of** **this side effect. The Lady of Fire and Lady of Water are engaged in an** **active cosmic struggle against the Abyss Circle while simultaneously** **destroying the first gate. The Youngest Brother was expelled from** **Oreka at some point in the past and is actively seeking return. There** **is NO connection between the Elemental Lords and the Abyss** **Circle—they are entirely separate cosmologies from different** **planes.*

### The Ascended Gods

Following the Fall of Aldenheim, mortal Kin who performed acts of extraordinary sacrifice or consequence ascended to godhood. Apotheosis was not possible before the Fall of Aldenheim—it is a new phenomenon in Oreka, barely 300 years old. The Ascended are not creator-gods—they are apotheosed mortals. Most are human, which is itself a theological mystery acknowledged in-world among theologians.

**The Ascended Gods are full gods.** Mechanically, they have the same abilities as any god in any D&D setting. They grant spells to clerics, answer prayers, and wield divine power. They are not diminished or lesser deities—they are the real thing.

**Apotheosis is morally neutral.** It responds to the magnitude and consequence of the act, not the moral character of the actor. This principle is proven by Hareem, the only evil Ascended God.

**Apotheosis requires attunement to all four elements.** This is not limited to Orekan attunement—any being with full four-element attunement qualifies. Pure Dómnathar, who possess no connection to elemental power, cannot ascend. This constraint is the foundation of the Dómnathar apotheosis plot (see Chapter 7).

| **God** | **Origin** | **Portfolio** | **Alignment** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Cinvarin, the Five Witnesses | Five druids at Aldenheim | Unity, elements, sacrifice | Neutral Good |
| Hareem, the Golden Rose | Bard who slew the Twelve Kings | Revenge, music, justice | Chaotic Evil |
| Tarvek Wen, Doombringer | Liberator | Justice, oaths, protection | Lawful Good |
| Ludus Galerius, Stone’s Hand | Warden of ruins | Earth, endurance, travel | Neutral Good |
| Apela Kelsoe, Windrider | Sky pathfinder | Air, travel, luck | Chaotic Good |
| Kaile’a, Mistress of Waves | Mariner-saint | Water, trade, community | Neutral Good |
| Gonmareck Ritler, Gunny | Smith-warrior | Metal, honor, tactics | Lawful Good |
| Semyon, the Hearth Mother | Healer | Family, healing, hearth | Neutral Good |
| The Hand Unanswered | Dying child of Aldenheim | Compassion, martyrdom | Neutral Good |
| The Unnamed Warrior King | Contested | War, kingship | Disputed (intentionally ambiguous) |

Cinvarin is the first Ascended God. Hareem is the second. Hareem is the only evil Ascended God. All others are Good-aligned; the Unnamed Warrior King is deliberately “Disputed.”

**Hareem’s Chaotic Evil alignment recontextualizes her portfolio:** “Revenge, music, justice” under CE becomes retributive justice—the kind that shatters worlds. She is worshipped by the wronged, the desperate, angry bards, and grieving parents. The theological question of whether evil acts can produce gods exists as an active debate among in-world theologians and connects directly to the Dómnathar apotheosis plot.

**Monster Manual Implication:** *Creatures that serve, guard, or are** **corrupted by Ascended Gods should reflect mortal themes—sacrifice,** **grief, memory, consequence—rather than primordial elemental force.** **Hareem-linked creatures should evoke rage, grief, and retribution.*

## 2. THE ELEMENTAL FRAMEWORK — HOW ELEMENTS SHAPE ALL LIFE

Every living thing native to Oreka exists in relationship to the four elements: Earth/Stone, Fire, Water/Ice, and Wind/Sky. This is not metaphorical—it is a tangible, supernatural reality that shapes biology, magic, and ecology.

**Important exception:** Not all beings exist within the elemental framework. The Dómnathar possess no connection to elemental power whatsoever (see Chapter 7). Breach-origin peoples (goblins, wargs, hobgoblins, orcs, ogres, kobolds) arrived from another world and exist outside Oreka’s native elemental harmony. However, Breach-origin peoples can and do gain elemental attunement over several generations of living in Oreka. This has profound implications for free goblin and warg communities that have been in Oreka for 300 years.

### The Four Elements

| **Element** | **Opposed**** ****Element** | **Energy**** ****Type** | **Associated**** ****Terrain** | **Associated**** ****Kin** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Earth/Stone | Wind/Sky | Acid | Mountains, caves, plains | Visetri Dwarves, Orean Humans, Giants |
| Fire | Water/Ice | Fire | Volcanoes, forges, deserts | Rarozhki Dwarves, Taraf-Imro Humans |
| Water/Ice | Fire | Cold | Rivers, seas, coasts, marshes | Pekakarlik Dwarves, Eruskan Humans, Halflings |
| Wind/Sky | Earth/Stone | Electricity | Forests, skies, high passes | All Elves, Mytroan Humans |

### Elemental Attunement in Creatures

All Kin possess Elemental Tolerance: Resistance 2 against energy damage from their primary element. This is intentionally spiritual and symbolic—a marker of elemental identity, not a scaling combat mechanic. It does not increase with level. Giants and Half-Giants, with All-Element Concord, gain Resistance 2 to all four types. Kin spellcasters gain +1 caster level for spells aligned with their element and −1 for opposed-element spells.

**Monster Manual Implication:** *Every creature entry should specify** **its Elemental Affinity. For Dómnathar:** **“**Elemental Affinity: None —** **Extraplanar.**”** **The** **“**Elemental Infused**”** **template (see Chapter 11) allows** **standard OGL creatures to be made Oreka-native.*

## 3. KIN-SENSE — THE RESONANCE SYSTEM

Kin-sense is the most important metaphysical concept in Oreka and the single most critical system for creature design. It is a supernatural resonance shared by all Kin peoples, functioning like a sixth sense that identifies “who belongs.” It operates within 60 feet normally (30 feet in elemental disturbance, 120 feet in deep calm), passes through barriers up to 5 feet thick, and cannot be suppressed by the Kin character except through the Deceiver’s Feat.

Kin-sense blockers: lead, worked Dómnathar metal, and False Silence block it entirely. **Kin-sense is NOT magic.** It cannot be dispelled, counterspelled, or suppressed by antimagic field. Inside an anti-magic zone, spells fail and magic items go dark, but Kin-sense still works. Only False Silence and related Dómnathar effects can suppress Kin-sense. This makes the Dómnathar categorically different from any other threat—they reach deeper than magic.

### What Kin-Sense Reveals

**Harmonic (Kin) resonance conveys:** what the person is (elf, human, dwarf, etc.) and their elemental attunement. It functions like a voice—those who know you personally can recognize your individual signature, just as you recognize a friend’s voice in a crowd. Strangers register as their race and element; familiar individuals are identifiable.

### Resonance Categories

| **Category** | **What It Feels Like** | **What Registers This**** ****Way** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Harmonic (Kin) | Warm presence; race and element readable; individual recognition possible | All true Kin: Elves, Dwarves, Halflings, Humans, Half-Giants |
| Wild Static | Present, alive, but fundamentally different | Tanuki, native Oreka animals, beasts (Oreka-native only) |
| Warm Static | Faint, unreadable background noise | Simple animals, insects, plants with minimal awareness |
| Breach Static | Alien, unsettling — a wrong note in the harmony | All Breach-origin peoples: Goblins, Wargs, Hobgoblins, Orcs, Ogres, Kobolds (diminishes over generations as attunement develops) |
| Null Resonance (Silent) | A wound; absence that hurts to perceive | Silentborn, Severed, Oath-Broken Kin |
| Void / Absolute Silence | Deliberate, predatory wrongness — unsettling gap | Dómnathar, true Deceivers (no check required to detect) |
| No Registration | Simply absent, like furniture | Undead (except ghosts: faint flicker, DC 20), Constructs, Farborn, Kin using Deceiver’s Feat |
| Raw Static | Overwhelming, painful at close range | Pure elementals (Will DC 15 within 10 ft or dazzled 1 rd) |

**Breach Static diminishes over generations.** Breach-origin peoples can and do gain elemental attunement over several generations of living in Oreka. Free goblin and warg communities that have been in Oreka for 300 years are already changing. This makes the Breach Static category a transitional state, not a permanent brand—though the process is slow enough that most current Breach-origin individuals still trigger it.

### The Three-Layer Supernatural Framework

Oreka’s supernatural reality operates on three independent layers:

| **Layer** | **Source** | **Nature** | **Suppressed**** ****By** | **Voluntary**** ****Suppress** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Layer 1: Soul Resonance (Kin-Sense) | Elemental framework, embedded in Kin souls at creation | Not magic. Cannot be dispelled or suppressed by anti-magic | False Silence, worked Dómnathar metal, Void energy, lead | Deceiver’s Feat (only) |
| Layer 2: Elemental Power (Magi Magic) | Direct elemental framework channel | Magic, but draws from elemental forces directly | Anti-magic zones, counterspells, dispel effects | N/A |
| Layer 3: Standard Magic (Arcane/Divine) | Varies (study, divine patron, innate) | Magic | Anti-magic zones, counterspells | N/A |

### Interaction Matrix

| **Scenario** | **Kin-Sense** | **Magi Magic** | **Standard**** ****Magic** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Inside anti-magic zone | ✔ YES | ✘ NO | ✘ NO |
| Inside False Silence | ✘ NO | ✔ YES | ✔ YES |
| In Dómnathar tunnel | ✘ NO (suppressed) | ✔ YES | ✔ YES |
| Both anti-magic + False Silence | ✘ NO | ✘ NO (anti-magic) | ✘ NO (anti-magic) |
| Normal conditions | ✔ YES | ✔ YES | ✔ YES |

**Standard magic is NOT affected by Dómnathar presence.** Only Kin-sense (Layer 1) is suppressed by False Silence and Dómnathar effects. Both Magi magic (Layer 2) and standard arcane/divine magic (Layer 3) function normally in Dómnathar tunnels, False Silence zones, and resonance-dead corridors. The Dómnathar’s weapon is soul-level, not magical.

### False Silence (Personal Cloak Mechanics)

**False Silence is a supernatural ability (Su).** It is a personal cloak on ONE Dómnathar—soul-level interference that cannot be dispelled and cannot be detected by detect magic. It is NOT a zone effect. The cloaked Deceiver simply doesn’t register—a hole shaped like a person.

**DC:** 10 + Deceiver’s HD + Charisma modifier. **Duration:** CHA mod × 10 minutes per use. **Uses/day:** HD ÷ 3 (minimum 1). **Concentration:** Required. If damaged: Concentration check (DC 10 + damage) or cloak drops.

Only masks Kin-sense. Does NOT grant invisibility, silence, or mundane disguise. Does not suppress Magi magic or standard magic. Infiltration is a layered operation.

### Kin-Sense Detection DCs and Racial Bonuses

| **Race** | **Bonus** | **Reasoning** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Half-Giants | +4 | All-Element Concord; broadest resonance |
| Elves | +2 | Secondborn; deeply attuned; long-lived |
| Dwarves | +2 | Thirdborn; strong elemental identity |
| Halflings | +1 | Fourthborn; perceptive but less intense |
| Humans | +0 | Fifthborn; variable; baseline |

**Passive detection:** d20 + WIS mod + Racial bonus vs. DC, with −10 penalty. Vague unease only. **Active detection:** Move action. d20 + WIS mod + Racial bonus vs. DC. Full check.

### Tiered Success (vs. False Silence)

| **Beat DC By** | **Result** | **Mechanical Effect** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 0–4 | Something feels off. Can’t localize. | Know False Silence is active; not which individual |
| 5–9 | Wrongness localizes to an area. | Approximate location (within 10 ft) |
| 10+ | Cloak cracks. Void bleeds through. | Pinpoint individual; true signature revealed |

### Situational Modifiers

| **Condition** | **Modifier** |
| --- | --- |
| Deep calm | +2 to check |
| Elemental disturbance | −2 to check |
| Deceiver within 10 ft | +4 to check |
| Deceiver at edge of range | −2 to check |
| Prior False Silence experience | +2 to check |
| Multiple Kin scanning simultaneously | +1 per extra scanner |
| Deceiver emotional or injured | −2 to False Silence DC |
| Worked Dómnathar metal area | +2 to False Silence DC |

### Special Cases

**Half-Dómnathar**

Register as “cracked” or “discordant” Kin—wrong but alive. Detecting the specific nature requires active concentration (move action) and a Kin-sense check.

**Disguised Creatures**

Mundane disguises do not fool Kin-sense (a human in dwarf armor still reads as human). Magical disguises create false resonance; active Kin-sense check vs. spell DC or Disguise check to detect the discrepancy.

### The Deceiver’s Feat

**Type:** General Feat. **Prerequisites:** WIS 15, character level 6th, must have been exposed to Void Silence or Null Resonance. Must find a teacher (person to person, in secret). Cannot be taken at character creation except by DM approval.

**Benefit:** Standard action: suppress Kin-sense signature. Register as No Registration (absent, like furniture). NOT Void Silence.

**Cost — Bidirectional blindness:** While suppressed, you cannot sense others via Kin-sense. Going dark means going blind.

**Scope — Personal only.** The Deceiver’s Feat suppresses the user’s own Kin-sense signature. It cannot be projected onto, extended to, or used to mask other creatures, mounts, companions, or objects. A Deceiver riding a horse does not mask the horse. A Deceiver standing next to a friend does not mask the friend.

**Magi exception:** A Magi using the Deceiver’s Feat loses Kin-sense (Layer 1) but retains Magi magic (Layer 2). Invisible to soul-perception, armed with elemental magic. Uniquely dangerous.

**Reactivation:** Standard action. Brief flicker: anyone within 30 ft actively scanning gets a free check (DC 15) to notice someone appeared.

**Social consequences:** The name is the punishment. Discovery means exile, horror, or violence. The technique is ancient and Kin-born—it predates the Shattering of Man. Factions that train it: Anacrusis, Silent Concord, Shrouded Court, Dómnathar handlers.

### Etymology of ‘Deceiver’

The word “Deceiver” existed BEFORE the Dómnathar arrived. It referred to Kin who suppressed their own Kin-sense—spies, assassins, or outcasts who could go dark. Kin Deceivers were active during the Shattering of Man, adding an espionage dimension to that civil war. When the Dómnathar arrived registering as Absolute Silence, the Kin used the darkest word they already had. “Deceiver” is a slur with layers—comparing the Dómnathar to the worst traitors in Kin history.

## 4. THE PEOPLES OF OREKA — RACES, CULTURES, AND CREATURE INTERACTIONS

Understanding who lives in Oreka is essential for creature design. Monsters exist in relationship to the peoples who encounter them—as predators, guardians, sacred beings, corrupted remnants, or alien threats.

### The Order of Creation (True Kin)

| **Order** | **Race** | **Creator** | **Element** | **Subraces** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Firstborn (extinct) | Giants | All four Lords | All four | None (unified race); 20–30 ft tall; immortal but unable to reproduce |
| Secondborn | Elves | Youngest Brother (Wind) | Wind primary | Hasura (artists/lightweavers), Pasua (storytellers/charmers), Na’wasua (stargazers/seers), Kovaka (stonebound warriors) |
| Thirdborn | Dwarves | Lady of Fire | Earth/Fire | Visetri (stone-forged traditionalists), Pekakarlik (river engineers, Small-sized, webbed fingers/toes, mossy green skin), Rarozhki (volcanic smiths), Aldenheim (extinct) |
| Fourthborn | Halflings | Lady of the Sea | Water | Four subraces exist, but outsiders cannot distinguish between them and Halflings do not discuss the differences. The subraces are a closely guarded cultural matter. |
| Fifthborn | Humans | A Giant and an Elf, with the Youngest Brother’s blessing | All (varies by culture) | Eruskan (mariners), Mytroan (nomads), Taraf-Imro (smiths/warriors), Orean (farmers/builders) |

Giants eventually crumbled to dust in a process the Elves called Thalorien (“the stone’s sleep”). Kharazhad, a fortress-forge in a caldera, is the greatest Rarozhki hold.

### Canon Ruling: Mixed Heritage

**Children of two different Kin races are born as one race or the other,**** ****never a hybrid.** No half-elves exist in Oreka. A child of a human and an elf is either human or elf—the elemental framework does not permit blended Kin souls. This is a fundamental law of Orekan metaphysics.

**This rule applies only to Kin.** The Farborn are not Kin—they are humans from another world whose metaphysics operated differently. The Gilded Standard Company included half-orcs, half-elves, and other hybrids that are products of their home world’s different rules. These individuals exist in Oreka as living anomalies: their hybrid heritage is real but could not have been produced here. See the Farborn sidebar (Chapter 4a) for details.

### Hybrid Peoples

| **People** | **Origin** | **Kin-Sense** | **Notes** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Half-Giants | Rites binding Giant essence into mortal lines | Full Kin (All-Element Concord) | LA +1; “Cousin” is a slur; +4 Kin-sense racial bonus makes them the best Dómnathar detectors; ideal apotheosis vessel (DM-facing) |
| Silentborn | Child of Kin and Deceiver | Null Resonance (wound-like absence) | Feared, tragic; Silent Concord faction; apotheosis candidate (DM-facing) |
| Half-Dómnathar | Dómnathar/Kin hybrid | Cracked/discordant Kin | LA +0; darkvision 60 ft, sleep immunity, light sensitivity, ‘foreign soul’ trait; used as assassins, infiltrators; apotheosis candidate (DM-facing) |

### Non-Kin Peoples

| **People** | **Origin** | **Status** | **Kin-Sense /**** ****Notes** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Farborn (Gilded Standard Company) | Foreign humans from another plane | Settled near Lone Titan, Deepwater Marches; Neutral Good; ~28,000 population | No Registration (invisible). Farborn are isolated at the Titan; Kin interaction occurs primarily during trade meets. 300 years of good trading and helping Kin has built trust. Farborn are slowly, tentatively becoming a fifth human kin. |
| Goblins | Deceiver auxiliaries; broke free at Dark Dawn | Free tribes in Deepwater Marches | Breach Static (diminishing over generations as attunement develops) |
| Wargs | Deceiver war-beasts; broke free at Dark Dawn | Independent faction; highly intelligent | Breach Static. NOT mounts—sentient; ride only by consent. |
| Hobgoblins | Deceiver NCOs; some freed | Iron Tribes (free) vs. Deceiver-aligned | Breach Static. Disciplined, Iron Law culture. |
| Orcs | Deceiver auxiliaries | Mostly still Deceiver-aligned | Breach Static. Brutal, relentless; scattered warbands. |
| Tanuki | Forest spirits; native to Oreka | Kin-adjacent | Wild Static (NOT Breach—they are Oreka-native). Raccoon-folk; shapeshifters, illusionists. |
| Ogres | Deceiver shock troops | Remnant warbands | Breach Static. Towering brutes; feared. |

**Monster Manual Implication:** *Post-Dark Dawn non-Kin peoples are** **NOT monolithic evil races. Include variants for free** **vs. Deceiver-aligned. Breach-origin peoples gain attunement over** **generations—free goblin tribes 300 years in are transitioning.*

### 4a. FARBORN: HUMANS BUT NOT KIN

The Farborn represent a unique category in Oreka’s metaphysics. They are biologically human—indistinguishable from Kin humans in appearance, physiology, and lifespan—but they are not Kin. They were not created by the Elemental Lords, they carry no elemental attunement, and they register as No Registration on Kin-sense: simply absent, like furniture.

**Farborn vs. Kin Humans — Key Differences**

| **Trait** | **Kin Humans (Eruskan,**** ****Mytroan, Taraf-Imro,**** ****Orean)** | **Farborn Humans** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Origin** | Created by a Giant and an Elf with the Youngest Brother’s blessing | Foreign-born; arrived through the Silence Breach as Deceiver auxiliaries |
| **Elemental**** ****Attunement** | Yes — varies by culture (Water, Wind, Fire, Earth) | None at birth. Emerging attunement after 300 years in Oreka (the “Titanbreed Paragon” phenomenon) |
| **Kin-Sense**** ****Registration** | Harmonic (Kin) — race and element readable | No Registration — invisible, absent |
| **Elemental Tolerance** | Resistance 2 to primary element | None |
| **Caster Level**** ****Modifier** | +1 aligned / −1 opposed element | None |
| **Mixed Heritage Rule** | Children of two Kin races are one or the other, never hybrid | Farborn home world permitted hybrids; half-elves and half-orcs exist among original Farborn stock |
| **Apotheosis**** ****Eligibility** | Yes (if all four elements attained) | Not currently — no elemental attunement. The emerging Titanbreed Paragon could change this |
| **Cultural Status** | Full Kin; recognized by all | Slowly, tentatively becoming a fifth human kin after 300 years of trust-building |

The original Gilded Standard Company included half-orcs, half-elves, and a small cadre of foreign dwarves—hybrids and non-humans that are products of their home world’s different metaphysical rules. Three centuries of intermarriage within the Farborn community and occasional unions with Kin humans have diluted these foreign bloodlines, but individuals with clearly non-Kin features still appear. These are curiosities, not scandals—the Farborn do not share Oreka’s metaphysical prohibition on hybrids because they were never subject to it.

**DM NOTE:** *The emerging** **“**Titanbreed Paragon**”** **phenomenon—faint** **elemental resonance appearing in Farborn children raised on the Lone** **Titan—is a metaphysical event with campaign-altering implications.** **If Farborn can develop elemental attunement, they may eventually** **register on Kin-sense, qualify for apotheosis, and fully integrate** **into Orekan metaphysics. This is a slow process, not yet confirmed,** **and deeply interesting to the Dómnathar.*

## 5. HISTORY THAT SHAPES MONSTERS — KEY EVENTS AND THEIR AFTERMATH

### The Age of Giants (Deep Past)

The Giants built the first civilizations along the Great River and in the Infinite Desert. They were immortal but could not reproduce, and eventually crumbled to dust (Thalorien). Their ruins fill the Infinite Desert, haunted by Sand Wraiths. Each of the seven regions of Oreka contains a Tomb of Kings—a great Giant burial site.

**Monster Manual Implication:** *Giant-era ruins contain guardian** **constructs, rune-bound elementals, and creatures sustained by ancient** **elemental circles still functioning millennia later. Ember Drakes nest** **in their volcanic forges. River Serpents guard their water temples.*

### Pre-War Kin Deceivers (Pre-Shattering)

Before the Dómnathar ever arrived, Kin who learned to suppress their own Kin-sense existed in Oreka. The Deceiver’s Feat is older than the Shattering of Man. These pre-war Deceivers—spies, assassins, or outcasts who could go dark—were feared and reviled. The word “Deceiver” was the darkest label a Kin could bear, and it was a Kin-born word for a Kin-born sin.

### The Shattering of Man (~150 KC)

Oreka saw four Keepers in all: the Pre-Keeper, a leader before the formal crowning; the First Crowned Keeper and the Second Crowned Keeper, who ruled wisely; and the Third Crowned Keeper, who proved the weakest and most foolish of them all. The Third Crowned Keeper was too weak and foolish to hold his realm. Lords of the four human kin argued over who should rule and a war broke out. The elves chose sides in what would be their greatest shame, the failure to guide man. Aldenheim, the Visetri, and the Rarozhki joined with the Taraf-Imro as loyalists. The Pekakarlik joined the rebellion. Kin Deceivers were active on both sides of the conflict, adding an espionage dimension. Many cities were burned to ruins and the Kin separated as so many siblings who had argued over a now broken toy. Each of the four human Kin blame the others for the Shattering—the Eruskans blame the Taraf-Imro, the Taraf-Imro blame the Oreans, the Oreans blame everyone, and the Mytrone consider it proof that centralized governance was always doomed to fail. No human subrace accepts responsibility, and the mutual recrimination has never healed.

### The Deceivers’ War (~430–452 KC)

The most monster-generating event in Oreka’s history. A foreign mercenary army led by the Dómnathar arrived through a misfired Assault Gate—the Silence Breach (Dorrach Kael, “The Conquest Door”)—in the southeastern foothills of the Gatefall Reach. The Dómnathar did not know Oreka existed until they had been here six months. The Breach was truly accidental.

The army included Dómnathar commanders, foreign elves, dwarves, humans, goblins, orcs, ogres, hobgoblins, kobolds, war-beasts, and creatures magical and monstrous. The host marched north through the Gap, across the Gatefall Reach and the Eternal Steppe, and into the Infinite Desert. While crossing the desert, one-third of the host—the Lost Third—reversed course and marched back south through the Gate of Fire into the Gatefall Reach, then west onto the Eternal Steppe (see Chapter 14 for the full account). The remaining two-thirds continued north, devastating Hillmeet, Foxfen, Whistlebank, and Mossgrove, and ultimately besieging Aldenheim. After the Fall of Aldenheim, the northern survivors scattered westward.

### The Siege and Fall of Aldenheim (~450 KC)

The dwarves of Aldenheim stood alone after the Twelve Kings of Man universally refused aid and the elven armies arrived too late.

**Player-facing history:** The Deceiver host used false giants—constructs or illusions that appeared to be the legendary Firstborn—to trick the Aldenheim dwarves into opening their gates. The gates were breached on day 10. The city fell on day 42.

**DM NOTE:** *DM truth: The siege continued underground for 100 days** **after the surface city’s destruction, totaling 142 days. The Aldenheim** **dwarves fought a grinding subterranean war even after the city above** **was lost. Five druids sacrificed themselves in a ritual that melted** **the mountain, destroyed the Deceiver host, and created the Lament of** **Kings—a blasted plain sitting atop the flattened ruins of Aldenheim,** **where Kin-sense is permanently unstable. The five druids became** **Cinvarin, the first Ascended God.*

### The Lament of Kings (451 KC)

The bard Hareem, enraged by the kings’ refusal to aid Aldenheim, killed all twelve human monarchs by drawing the air from the chamber—suffocating them with her own breath as the final offering. Hareem died in the act and ascended as the second Ascended God: the Golden Rose, Chaotic Evil. This act shattered the old political order forever.

### The Reckoning (450–452 KC)

The chaotic period encompassing the Fall of Aldenheim, the Lament of Kings, and the Battle of Dark Dawn. The old world ends; a new one begins.

### Wars of the Shattered Host (1–300 AL)

For 300 years, surviving Dómnathar houses and Deceiver fragments have fought each other in Oreka’s shadows. Not all Deceiver creatures are allies—they may fight each other.

### 5a. THE OREKA DATING SYSTEM & MASTER TIMELINE

**Old Calendar — Keeper Crowned (KC)**

Begins with the crowning of the first Keeper by the last living Giant. Today, only scholars and long-lived elves use KC dates.

**Current Calendar — After the Lament (AL)**

Begins with the first Lament Games. Year 1 AL ≈ 452 KC. Campaign present: Year 300 AL (≈ 752 KC).

### Master Timeline

| **Date** | **Event** |
| --- | --- |
| Pre-KC | Age of Giants. Tombs of Kings built in each of the seven regions. |
| Year 1 KC | First Keeper crowned by the last Giant. |
| Pre-Shattering | The Deceiver’s Feat is developed. Kin Deceivers exist as spies and assassins. |
| ~150 KC | The Shattering of Man. Third Crowned Keeper too weak and foolish to hold the realm. Succession dispute, civil war. Kin Deceivers active on both sides. Cities burned. Kin separated. |
| ~430 KC | Deceivers’ War begins. Dómnathar arrive through misfired Assault Gate (Silence Breach). They did not know Oreka existed until 6 months in. |
| ~430–450 KC | Host marches north. One-third (the Lost Third) splits off in the desert—disillusionment and suspicion combined with the belief that the desert had no end. They march south through the Gate of Fire and west onto the Eternal Steppe. |
| ~450 KC | Fall of Aldenheim. Gates breached day 10 via false giants. City falls day 42. Underground fighting continues 100 more days. Five druids melt the mountain. Cinvarin ascends. Northern survivors scatter westward. |
| 451 KC | Hareem kills the Twelve Kings. The Lament of Kings. Second apotheosis. |
| 450–452 KC | The Reckoning. Running War and Battle of Dark Dawn on the Eternal Steppe. Goblin and warg troops break free. Old world ends. |
| Year 1 AL (~452 KC) | First Lament Games. New era begins. |
| Year 300 AL (~752 KC) | Campaign present. |

*Elves who are 400+ years old were alive during the KC era and** **personally experienced the calendar changing.*

## 6. THE SEVEN REGIONS — ENVIRONMENT AND ECOLOGY GUIDE

| **#** | **Region** | **Position** | **Terrain** | **Key Creature**** ****Niches** | **Tomb of**** ****Kings**** ****Location** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Twin Rivers | Northwest | River valleys, forests, hills | River Serpents, forest spirits, Tanuki, trade-route predators | Present (specific site TBD) |
| 2 | Kinsweave | North-Central | Plains, lakes, rugged mountains, river valleys, volcanic zones, border kingdoms | Plains predators, Border Kingdom monsters, Lament of Kings creatures, Scorchspires fauna | Present (specific site TBD) |
| 3 | Tidebloom Reach | Northeast | Lakeside, tidal forests, marshes | Tidal creatures, Kailian Sea beasts, haunted ruins | Present — located in the far north near Hillmeet ruins |
| 4 | The Infinite Desert | Central Band | Equatorial desert, Giant ruins | Sand Wraiths, Ember Drakes, guardian constructs | Present (specific site TBD) |
| 5 | Deepwater Marches | Southwest | Dense jungle, Apelian Sea shore | Jungle predators, free goblin/warg creatures, Deceiver remnants, Flamewarg cult raiders | Present (specific site TBD) |
| 6 | Eternal Steppe | South-Central | Vast grasslands, nomadic territory | Steppe predators, herd beasts, Mytroan monsters | Present (specific site TBD) |
| 7 | Gatefall Reach | Southeast | Mixed forest, prairie, Silence Breach | Breach-warped creatures, Deceiver warbands, frontier beasts | Tomb of Kings (Gatefall Remnant base of operations) |

The Infinite Desert functionally separates the northern and southern tiers like an ocean would.

### Regional Detail: The Infinite Desert

Once the heart of the Giant empire. Flanked by the Emberfangs, Scorchspires, and Ashen Crown ranges. Ancient oases maintained by Pekakarlik Dwarves and Kovaka Elves sustain life—the Pekakarlik managing hydraulic systems and underground channels, the Kovaka tending stone structures and rune-circles. During the age of the Eke Concordant, the Na’wasua worked with the Taraf-Imro to raise great observatories into the skies above the desert. The desert earned its name—the Lost Third turned back because they did not believe it had an end, their disillusionment and suspicion crystallizing into betrayal. Dual elemental patronage is practiced at some desert settlements, reflecting the cooperative nature of survival in this harsh environment.

### Regional Detail: Deepwater Marches

Transformed by the Dark Dawn scatter into a contested wildland. Dense jungle around the Apelian Sea hosts Kin conclaves, free goblin tribes, wargbond communities, Deceiver remnants, and the Farborn at the Lone Titan. The Dómnathar tower on the southern sea spur is their hidden stronghold in the region—quietly rebuilding for 300 years. Flamewarg cults, originally descended from Gatefall Remnant cavalry, spread westward into the Marches over the centuries, drawn by the terrain’s suitability for their fire-and-ambush tactics and the region’s lack of centralized authority to oppose them.

### Regional Detail: Tidebloom Reach

Burned ruins of Hillmeet, Foxfen, Whistlebank, and Mossgrove haunted by the northern campaign. Ghost-like creatures, war-damaged undead, and beasts adapted to tainted soil.

### Regional Detail: Gatefall Reach

The southeastern frontier where the Silence Breach opened and the Deceiver army first entered Oreka. Three centuries later, the Breach scar persists as a Kin-sense dead zone. The region’s terrain transitions from open steppe grasslands in the west and northwest through the crescent forests of the center and east to the mountain foothills framing the Gap in the southeast. Key landmarks include the Scar Road (the compacted path of the original Deceiver march), the Burnt Warrens (underground burrow-forts built by scattered Deceiver warbands after Dark Dawn), and the Windstone Circle (a ring of five Giant-era standing stones on the Gatefall Grasslands, shared by Mytrone and Pasua for joint ceremonies). The Gatefall Remnant—half of the Lost Third’s scattered forces—established operations centered on the Tomb of Kings.

### Major Geographic Features

**Giant’s Teeth:** Two parallel mountain ranges that flank either side of the Infinite Desert and wrap all the way around the world, touching all seven regions. They are the most prominent continental-scale landform in Oreka, serving as natural barriers, trade route corridors, and monuments to the Age of Giants.

**Scorchspires:** A volcanic mountain range rich in minerals and heat, located where the Kinsweave region meets the Infinite Desert. Home to Rarozhki holds including Kharazhad. Ember Drakes nest in their forges.

**Northern Lament Range:** A mountain range north of the Giant’s Teeth in Kinsweave, extending from the ruins of Pyree and Andrio to Rivertop and Highridge. Scarred by the Deceivers’ War and the Lament of Kings, it influences the Great River’s course and bears deep historical significance.

**Kailian Sentinels:** Isolated mountains along the Kailian Sea coast in Kinsweave, separating Lakeshore Bay and Lakewell Cove. Composed of basalt and limestone, they feature tidal caves and serve as navigational landmarks.

**Mistveil Ridges:** Mountains south of the Seaspray Lagoon in Kinsweave, adjacent to the Sundrift Veil. Made of sandstone and basalt, shrouded in mist. Tied to legends of protection during past wars.

**Seaspray Lagoon:** A small offshoot of the Kailian Sea south of Lakeshore in Kinsweave, a shallow bay formed by tidal and river influences. Used for fishing and trade, enhanced by water spirit rituals.

## 7. THE DÓMNATHAR & THE ABYSS CIRCLE — THE HIDDEN ENEMY

The Dómnathar are obsidian-skinned, white-haired deep elves from another world entirely—NOT fallen Kin, NOT native to Oreka. They are extraplanar outsiders whose souls are tuned to the Abyss Circle rather than Oreka’s elemental harmony. To Kin-sense they register as Absolute Silence. Their capital, Dómnathar-Zhuan, is on their home world, not in Oreka.

**The Dómnathar did not know Oreka existed until they had been here six**** ****months.** The Silence Breach was a misfired Assault Gate. Their invasion was opportunistic, not planned.

### Dómnathar Lifespan and Society

**Dómnathar can live up to 1,000 years.** The pre-invasion house leaders (aged 187–298 at the time of the Breach) are still alive in the campaign present. They have personal memory of their home world and 300 years of experience in Oreka. This gives the Dómnathar villain faction deep personal continuity.

Dómnathar society is matrilineal (Motherlines) but NOT strictly matriarchal—either sex can rule. Eleven Great Houses: 10 peer Houses (Circle of Knives) + 1 Paramount (Vael’domin, intentionally left as DM’s choice).

### Dómnathar Elemental Disconnection

**The Dómnathar possess no Elemental Affinity.** Their souls are attuned to the Abyss Circle rather than to Oreka’s elemental framework, and their primary magical traditions draw upon that connection. However, lacking an Elemental Affinity does not bar the Dómnathar from wielding elemental magic—they are simply less powerful in it than Kin races, who carry an innate resonance that the Dómnathar do not share. A Dómnathar sorcerer can command fire or bend water, but will never match a Kin caster of equal skill working within their native element. Stat blocks: “Elemental Affinity: None — Extraplanar.” This disadvantage, rather than an absolute prohibition, is what drives their civilization—they enslave elementally-attuned beings across worlds to compensate for their own lesser attunement.

### The Eleven Great Houses

| **House** | **Theme** | **Patron** | **Creature**** ****Implications** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
